COVID REVIEW  Really nice and comfortable seating built pretty much on the street on Bedford Ave. There are 5 tables with electric heaters - it was a cold day out but the heaters and newly built enclosure did the trick.  No QR menu, they hand you regular hardcover menus.  Since there are only a few tables with heaters we decided to wait 5 minutes for one to open up. The staff was great, quickly sat us down once the table was ready and took our drink orders (I ordered a hot cider with rum).  Ordered fried cheese and potato pierogis as an appetizer- they were definitely my favorite item we ordered from the menu. Also had the beef goulash and chicken cutlet, both of which were great.  Only potential downside would be the location - Bedford is sometimes quite busy and noisy.  TLDR: highly recommend to stop by for some pierogis!

You know, as fellow Pole, I’ve never heard of this place. But, there’s a reason TimeOut NY rates this the best place for Polish food: it is! Now, I didn’t see a single Polish person in this place, but, that shouldn’t stop you. The food is authentic, and the vibe is great. We had the Polish platter, and it did not disappoint. The platter comes with pierogies, a classic Polish dumpling. (We had the potato/cheese and sauerkraut/mushroom pierogies. Super!) There’s also stuffed cabbage on the plate, which is a traditional Polish dish of rice/meat wrapped in a cabbage leaf. It was perfect. The was some amazing Polish kielbasa on the platter as well. For dessert, we had the traditional sweet cheese crepes. (Crepes are really French, and traditionally Polish dish is blintzes. The guy at the place didn’t know the difference.) Dziupla has some great dark and on tap and Polish beers. We highly recommend the dark ones. It was a relatively affordable and enjoyable NYC dining experience.

This was one of the best meals I've had of 2017. At first , I was a little wary of a Polish restaurant, but I could have not be more surprised. The mushroom and sauerkraut pierogies were a great starter on a cold winter night. My boyfriend got the Kurobuta Pork Chop, and it was as tender and delicious as a steak. I had the BBQ Wild Boar Ribs, and I was blown away. They were so flavorful and fell off the bone. It is not like your traditional BBQ, more like a sweet and savory tomato braised sauce that was amazing. We lingered for a drink after dinner and the service was great. They were very patient with us taking our time deciding, and changing our minds multiple times. This place is a well priced secret, a jem in Brooklyn that I look forward to going back to soon.
